ArchaeologicalElement.name: Context
ArchaeologicalElement.description: The physical result of any single action, whether it leaves a positive or negative record within the stratigraphic sequence. (MoLAS 1994)

property.name: Site Code
property.description: Short code to signify the excavation site and often the year of excavation.

property.name: Context ID
property.description: Unique number or code for each Context.

property.name: AreaCode
property.description: Area or Trench: the working subdivision of an archaeological site.

property.name: Grid Location Reference
property.description: Reference number for the grid square(s) within which this Context falls.

property.name: Date Opened
property.description: Date (YYYY-MM-DD) on which the Context was first excavated.

property.name: Excavation Method
property.description: Method and conditions of archaeological excavation.

property.name: Elevation Datum Type
property.description: The type of elevation.

property.name: Highest Level
property.description: The highest elevation, or 'starting level', recorded for that context. This may be relative to the site grid, or real world co-ordinates, depending on the method of measurement.

property.name: Lowest Level
property.description: The lowest elevation recorded for that context. This may be relative to the site grid, or real world co-ordinates, depending on the method of measurement.

property.name: Target Spit Thickness
property.description: The minimum thickness of deposit

property.name: Minimum Context Thickness
property.description: The minimum thickness of the deposit based on the highest and lowest in each extent within the square.

property.name: Maximum Context Thickness
property.description: The maximum thickness of the deposit based on the highest and lowest in each extent within the square.

property.name: Context Comments
property.description: Additional comments on the description of the Context.

property.name: Artefacts Present
property.description: Whether or not artefacts were present in the {Context}.

property.name: Soil Compaction Type
property.description: The type of compaction of sediments in the deposit, eg 'Compact', 'Cemented' or 'Loose'.

property.name: Soil Texture
property.description: Proportions of different grain sizes within the deposit, eg if there is more sand to silt it should be described as a 'silty sand'.

property.name: Soil Texture Actual
property.description: Proportions of different grain sizes within the deposit, eg if there is more sand to silt it should be described as a 'silty sand'.

lookup.term: No Observation No Observation. Use the Texture helper to prefil this.
{Sand} A sand has a loose gritty feel and does not stick together. Individual sand grains can be seen or felt. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)
{Loamy_Sand} In a loamy sand particles barely stick together and a moulded piece of soil just holds its shape. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)
{Silty_Clay_Loam} A silty clay loam is like a clay loam but silty as well and smooth to the touch. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Clay_Loam} More easily moulded into a shape than a loam, a clay loam rolls out to a thin ribbon between the palms while a loam will break-up. When dry a clay loam will form a lump but is not as tough to break as a clay.(VDEPI 2009: AG0058)
{Sandy_Clay_Loam} A sandy clay loam is like a clay loam but sand grains can be felt (and heard - see Sandy Loam) (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)
{Silty_Clay} A silty clay is like a clay but smoother. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Clay} Clays are tough and can be moulded into shapes when moist. Clays form a long flexible ribbon when rubbed between the palms and the ribbon can often be bent into a U shape without breaking. Clays dry into very hard clods. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)
{Sandy_Clay} A sandy clay is like a clay but sand grains can be felt (and heard - see Sandy Loam). (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Silt_Loam} A silty loam is like a loam but has a smooth silky feel when a moist sample is pushed between the index finger and thumb. On drying a sample can form a hard lump but this may be broken by hand. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Loam} A loam breaks into crumbs but will tend to stick together. Sand grains cannot be felt in a moist sample which when squeezed will retain its shape when handled freely. Loams are usually soft to the feel. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Sandy_Loam} A sandy loam sticks together more than a loamy sand but can be easily broken. Individual sand grains can be felt and heard if a wet sample is rubbed between the index finger and thumb and held close to the ear. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

property.name: Geological Unit Number
property.description: The geological unit of the layer assigned by the geologist (typically decreasing numbers with depth).

property.name: Structure
property.description: The arrangement of primary soil particles into compound particles or aggregates.

lookup.term: {Single_Grain} Sediment that is broken into individual particles that do not stick together. Typically accompanies loose consistence in sandy sediments.
{Massive} Sediments that have no visible structure, are hard to break apart, and appear in very large clods.
{Laminated} Distinct bands of varying sediment texture (e.g. silts, medium sands, clays) that usually deposit at non-horizontal angles. Common in canals, reservoirs, and wells.
{Platy} Thin, flat plates of soil that lie horizontally. Usually found in compacted soil.
{Granular} Resembles cookie crumbs and is usually less than 0.5 cm in diameter. Commonly found in surface horizons where roots have been growing.
{Blocky} Irregular blocks that are usually 1.5 to 5.0 cm in diameter.
{Prismatic} Vertical columns of soil typically more than 5 cm long. Usually found in lower soil horizons.
{Columnar} Vertical columns of soil that have a white rounded salt 'cap' at the top. They occur very commonly in arid climates.

property.name: Structure Modifiers
property.description: Describe the degree to which the structure is developed. Also describe in the notes if the ped size is large, medium, or fine.

lookup.term: {Weak} Some structure is apparent, but it is inconsistent within the horizon.
{Moderate} Structure is moderately developed throughout the horizon.
{Strong} Structure is well-developed throughout the horizon.

property.name: Inclusions Gravel Fraction
property.description: Include amounts and qualities; i.e. 'Minor CaCO3 filaments' or 'Minor cultural material present'.

property.name: Upper Boundary
property.description: Describe the overall way in which the upper boundary of the horizon contacts the one above it. If a secondary boundary type applies, describe it in the comments.

lookup.term: {Merging} Horizon merges gradually with the one above it.
{Clear} Boundary is clearly defined but not sharp.
{Sharp/Straight} Boundary is clearly defined and sharp.
{Smooth} Boundary is apparent but not clearly defined.
{Continuous} Boundary is continuous across the exposed profile, but takes more than one form.
{Discontinuous} Boundary is discontinuous across the exposed profile, and takes more than one form.

property.name: Lower Boundary
property.description: Describe the overall way in which the lower boundary of the horizon contacts the one above it. If a secondary boundary type applies, describe it in the comments.

lookup.term: {Merging} Horizon merges gradually with the one above it.
{Clear} Boundary is clearly defined but not sharp.
{Sharp/Straight} Boundary is clearly defined and sharp.
{Smooth} Boundary is apparent but not clearly defined.
{Continuous} Boundary is continuous across the exposed profile, but takes more than one form.
{Discontinuous} Boundary is discontinuous across the exposed profile, and takes more than one form.

property.name: Soil Colour
property.description: The colour of soil sediment.

property.name: Compaction
property.description: The degree to which the sediment particles adhere to one another and require force to be separated. Follow this procedure to determine soil compaction/consistence. Take a ped (an aggregate of soil) from the soil horizon. If the soil is very dry, moisten the face of the profile with a water bottle first. Holding the ped between your thumb and forefinger, gently squeeze it until it pops or falls apart. Loose soil will not need to be squeezed, while soft soil will fall apart immediately. Slightly hard soil takes some pressure, while hard soil takes a lot of pressure. Very hard soil can only be broken apart along its structure using a digging tool, and cemented soil cannot be broken apart along its structure at all.

property.name: Disturbances
property.description: Disturbances evident in the deposit

property.name: Sorting
property.description: Assessment of the frequency with which particles of the same size occur.

lookup.term: {aVery_poorly_sorted} Particles are very different sizes and very unevenly distributed.
{bPoorly_sorted} Particles are different sizes and unevenly distributed.
{cModerately_sorted} Particles are mostly the same size and evenly distributed, but there are some larger particles.
{dWell_sorted} Particles are roughly the same size and evenly distributed.
